0\x9d he said.\nIhekweazu also said that samples would no longer be transferred from different parts of the country to a particular centre, as states now have their own laboratories.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cWith 69 Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR), 22 GeneXpert\xa0and 17 private laboratories for COVID-19 in Nigeria, testing opportunities is now closer to the people.\n\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s now up to the public healthcare work force to utilise them to full potential and raise more awareness on their importance in the response,\xe2\x80\x9d he said.\nThe director-general said that two new antigen-based rapid test kits were recently given for emergency use, licenced\xa0by the World Health Organisation (WHO) for COVID-19 response in three countries.\n\xe2\x80\x9cThey both have limitations as well as benefits, but won\xe2\x80\x99t replace the PCR tests.\n\xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re working to define the context of their usage,\xe2\x80\x9d he said.\nAccording to him, the two test kits have a shorter turnaround time and can help public health workers to initiate immediate health response.\nIhekweazu said digital surveillance tools had been activated in local government areas of the country, airports, points of entries and land borders\xa0to help improve the surveillance of vivid and other diseases.\nMeanwhile, the director-general\xa0 announced the untimely death of Mr Uche Njoku, a Logistic expert with the NCDC, who was shot by unknown gunmen while on an official trip.\nHe commiserated with his family and all frontline workers on the painful loss of Njoku.\n\xe2\x80\x9cWe also wish other workers in the vehicle that were injured a quick recovery.\n\xe2\x80\x9cThis incident underscores the danger that frontline workers face in the course of fighting the virus on our behalf.\n\xe2\x80\x9cWe urge all Nigerians to continue to pray for the safety of all frontline workers and their families,\xe2\x80\x9d he said. (NAN)\nShare this:TwitterFacebookLinkedInPinterestEmailPrintSkypeWhatsAp